SIMPLE: foray
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Foray
<hw>For"ay</hw> <pr>(f⟦ocr⟧r"⟦asl⟧ <it>or</it> f⟦osl⟧*r⟦amac⟧";
277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Another form of <ets>forahe</ets>. Cf.
<er>Forray</er>.]</ety> <def>A sudden or irregular incursion in border
warfare; hence, any irregular incursion for war or spoils; a raid.</def>
<rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The huge Earl Doorm, . . . ⟦br⟧
Bound on a <qex>foray</qex>, rolling eyes of prey.</q>
<rj><qau>Tennyson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Foray</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Foray
<hw>For"ay</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To pillage; to ravage.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He might <qex>foray</qex> our lands.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Forayer</ent>⟦br⟧
